## Are Blue Nile Rubies Real? Natural or Lab-Created?

**Blue Nile ruby rings use natural, earth-mined rubies — not lab-created.** Lab rubies exist and are significantly cheaper, but Blue Nile's preset ruby ring catalog uses genuine rubies.

**Are they heat-treated?** Almost certainly yes — and this is completely normal. Over 95% of commercial rubies are heat-treated to improve color intensity and clarity. Unlike emeralds (which use oil or resin to fill fractures), ruby heat treatment uses high temperatures to dissolve inclusions and intensify the red color. The treatment is permanent, stable, does not affect durability, and is universally accepted in the fine jewelry industry. It does not diminish value at this price point — you are paying for the color and the setting, not an "unheated" rarity premium.

**What quality are they?** Blue Nile doesn't publish grading reports for preset ruby rings the way they do for diamond rings. The rubies are selected to match each setting at the appropriate price point — an 8x6mm oval will be eye-clean and appropriately colored for that price. This is standard for all preset colored stone jewelry across reputable retailers.

**Origin matters for rubies.** Burmese (Myanmar) rubies — specifically the "pigeon blood" red with a slight blue fluorescence — are the most prized in the world. Thai rubies are darker and less expensive. Mozambique rubies have gained significant reputation in recent years and are now widely considered near-equivalent to Burmese. Blue Nile does not specify origin for preset rings at this price tier. If origin certification matters to you, you need a custom sourcing approach.

